Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Halve the @sweet potatoes{24%ounce}, then cut into wedges (like steak fries!). Trim and halve the @Brussels sprouts{16%ounce} lengthwise, then thinly slice into shreds. Toss the sweet potato wedges on a foil-lined #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Place in the oven for ~{20-25%minutes}, flipping halfway through cooking, until golden brown.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the @brown sugar{2%tablespoon} and the @blackening spice{2%tablespoon}. Season the @pork tenderloin{24%ounce} on all sides with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Coat the pork tenderloin on all sides with a thick layer of the brown sugar mixture. You may have some leftover.

Place the pork tenderloin on the baking sheet with the sweet potatoes and return to the oven for ~{15-20%minutes}, flipping halfway through cooking, until cooked to desired doneness.

Peel, core and dice the @Granny Smith apple{2}(peeled, cored and diced). Zest and halve the @lemon{1}(zested and juiced). Heat a large drizzle of @oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Add the shredded Brussels sprouts and the apple and cook, tossing, for ~{5-6%minutes}, until the Brussels sprouts are slightly golden brown. Stir in the @dried cranberries{2%ounce}, a pinch of lemon zest, and a squeeze of lemon juice (to taste). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Let the pork tenderloin rest for ~{5%minutes} before thinly slicing. Serve alongside the sweet potato wedges and Brussels-sprout apple hash. Enjoy!